SIMPLE: sing
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sing
<hw>Sing</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos> <conjf>Sung</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr> or
<conjf>Sang</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sung</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Singing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>singan</ets>; akin to
D. <ets>zingen</ets>, OS. & OHG. <ets>singan</ets>, G.
<ets>singen</ets>, Icel. <ets>syngja</ets>, Sw. <ets>sjunga</ets>, Dan.
<ets>synge</ets>, Goth. <ets>siggwan</ets>, and perhaps to E.
<ets>say</ets>, v.t., or cf. Gr. <?/<?/<?/ voice. Cf. <er>Singe</er>,
<er>Song</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To utter sounds with musical
inflections or melodious modulations of voice, as fancy may dictate, or
according to the notes of a song or tune, or of a given part (as alto,
tenor, etc.) in a chorus or concerted piece.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The noise of them that <qex>sing</qex> do I hear.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
xxxii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To utter sweet melodious sounds, as birds
do.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On every bough the briddes heard I <qex>sing</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Singing</qex> birds, in silver cages hung.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To make a small, shrill sound; <as>as, the air
<ex>sings</ex> in passing through a crevice</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O'er his head the flying spear⟦br⟧
<qex>Sang</qex> innocent, and spent its force in air.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To tell or relate something in numbers or verse; to
celebrate something in poetry.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bid her . . . <qex>sing</qex>⟦br⟧
Of human hope by cross event destroyed.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1344 --></p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To cry out; to complain.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They should <qex>sing</qex> if thet they were bent.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sing</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sing
<hw>Sing</hw> <pr>(s⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
utter with musical inflections or modulations of voice.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And they <qex>sing</qex> the song of Moses, the servant of God,
and the song of the Lamb.</q> <rj><qau>Rev. xv. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And in the darkness <qex>sing</qex> your carol of high praise.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To celebrate in song; to give praises to in verse;
to relate or rehearse in numbers, verse, or poetry.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Arms and the man I <qex>sing</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The last, the happiest British king,⟦br⟧
Whom thou shalt paint or I shall <qex>sing</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To influence by singing; to lull by singing; <as>as,
to <ex>sing</ex> a child to sleep</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To accompany, or attend on, with singing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I heard them <qex>singing</qex> home the bride.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Singe</ent>⟦br⟧
